And it was a god fucking damn cartoon. Fucking pathetic.
I tied my value, and my very being, to what I thought would turn out to be gold, but in the end it was the stone used to drown me.

And then, when it all went to hell, I lost everything that made me... me. All that’s left is fear, and resignation, and the echoing cackling of the voice in my head that told me from the start that I was wrong, that I was bad, that I didn’t deserve to be loved or validated

I defined myself by being stubborn and resilient, by not giving up, by clinging to the vain hope that I was right for once and telling myself it was self-assurance. I threw everything into proving that I could hold on and take it long enough to be validated and maybe rewarded.

I should have listened to my gut and given up. Quit before I was broken down into a shadow of my former self. Who am I, now, anyhow? I defined who I was by a fucking show I liked for years and when the show failed me, I failed myself alongside it.

And it wasn’t. Starting was worth it. Stepping up was worth it. But staying? No. I should have cut and run after I found my polycule.

Given the chance to re-do things, I would still join the fandom. I wouldnt give up my polycule for the world. But I would get out sooner.

I told myself that this time was it, that this time I was right for once, that I was good, that I would be validated and maybe even vindicated. That I would be rewarded for loyalty and tenacity. I wasn’t going to give up. I would see it through and it would be worth it.

I had so many warnings, too. From the universe itself, even. Broken stones, specific ones. Lost or damaged items, again specific ones. Bad feelings. Bad omens. Warnings from the universe to take care of myself. And I didn’t listen.

if only I had known it would all be lies. If only I had listened to the sad, tired voice in my heart that told me to stop fighting and give up hope. If only I had paid attention to the warnings instead of running on faith and blind optimism.

if only I hadn’t constantly had to defend myself, if I hadn’t constantly had to worry if I was being judged or getting things wrong, if I didn’t have to tell myself it would be worth it in the end, if the showrunners hadn’t spent the whole time promising it would be worth it...

If I do say something that turns out to be a lie that’s because the only person I’m good at lying to is myself. There’s a 90% chance that I believed exactly what I said at the time and a 10% chance that I’m just an idiot.

I mean I’m an idiot anyhow but you get the idea
Or like, remaining in the closet for my own safety but that’s a given. And I’m even bad at that lmao.

Growing up with compulsive liars who also constantly accused me of lying has given me A Thing about lying. In that I don’t do it to anyone who doesn’t have power over me, and even then they’re only little fibs to keep them from hurting me worse.

I don’t want anyone to try to be friends with me because they like an incomplete version of me. I put all of myself out there so you can make an informed decision. What you see is what you get. It’s kinda shabby and barely functions most of the time, but it’s honest.

Please know that even when I’m talking about being upset, I am not doing so to guilt people into comforting me. None of you are responsible for my health or well-being, and I want you to know that. I’m sharing every facet of Me out of honesty.

Twitter isn’t therapy and it isn’t my intention to use it as such. I don’t talk about my issues in the hopes of comfort and asspats (that’s what private discords and couch cuddles are for) but in the hopes that I can make someone else feel less alone, or understand themself more

Sometimes I feel bad about rambling about my own recovery/thought processes/introspection but I’ve actually been told by someone before that I’ve helped them by being so open and honest about my thoughts and feelings. So. Maybe I can help someone else.

It’s kind of weird to be healing to the point where I’m not in a constant state of suicidal ideation, passive or active
